'''Finches''' are often [[seed]]-eating [[passerine]] [[bird]]s, the many [[species]] of which are found chiefly in the northern hemisphere, but they also occur in [[Africa]], and one subfamily is endemic to the Neotropics.  The finch family, Fringillidae, also contains the Hawaiian honeycreepers ([[Drepanididae|Drepanidinae]]).

"Classic finches" are small to moderately large and have a strong [[beak]], usually [[cone (solid)|conical]] and in some species very large. All have 12 tail feathers and 9 primaries. These birds have a bouncing flight with alternating bouts of flapping and gliding on closed wings, and most sing well. Their nests are basket-shaped and built in trees.


